Regressing with T and E scalar anisotropies (no lensing B-modes)¶

To get more realistic simulations we include $E$ -modes polarization to the signal to be observed. So that, now pair differences encode a non-null signal. We keep 10 minutes as the gain drift time scale.

Contamination at the power spectrum level¶

Let's have look at the transfer function,

$ \mathcal{F}_{\ell} \equiv C^{sys}_{\ell} / C^{inp}_{\ell }$

TT¶

In [152]:
fig=pl.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
ll=l*(l+1)/pl.pi/2.
pl.subplot(121)
pl.title('TT')

pl.ylabel(r'$\mathcal{F}_{\ell}$   ', fontsize=20)

pl.semilogx(l, abs  (cldrifts[0][2:]    /cl[0][2: ])  , label ='pre-correct.'  )
pl.semilogx(l, (cldriftcorr[0][2:] )   / cl[0][2: ]   , label='post-correct.' )
pl.legend(loc='upper right')
pl.xlim([2,500])

pl.subplot(122)
pl.ylabel(r'$ | C^{sys}_{\ell} - C^{inp}_{\ell} | [K^2] $   ', fontsize=20)

pl.loglog(l, abs  (cldrifts[0][2:]    -cl[0][2: ])  , label ='pre-correct.'  )
pl.loglog(l, abs(cldriftcorr[0][2:]    - cl[0][2: ] )   , label='post-correct.' )
pl.loglog(l, abs  ( cl[0][2: ])*1e-3 ,'k', label = r'$  0.1 \% $ CMB TT '  )

pl.legend(loc='upper right')
pl.xlim([2,lmax])
Out[152]:
(2, 500)

(left) The TT transfer function of pre and post correction spectra (respectively in blue and orange) presents very interesting features. By injecting the gain drifts the $\mathcal{F}_\ell$ looks as a sort of noise component fluctuating around $1$, being essentially noisier at higher multipoles. On the other hand, correcting the gain drifts reduces a lot the noise into the spectra but introducing an extra component whose spectrum is $0.1 \% C_\ell^{TT}$( solid black in right panel)

the TE transfer function presents similar features as in EE. The gain correction strongly leaves a factor of 4 bias at the $\ell =4 $ multipole. In the bottomo panels we show the TE power spectra without any systematic leakage (solid black) and pre and post- gain correction (resp. solid blue and orange ). We zoomed into the multipole regions where the transfer function fluctuates more, i.e. $\ell \sim 4, 60, 200 $.
